text=:Category: MorphosyntacticDiversity%0a:Essential: {Category.MorphosyntacticDiversity$:essential}%0a:Title: Repetition clefts are for emphasis is what they’re for%0a:Author: saraht%0a:Section: A%0a:Completed: 15.04.2021 - 14:27%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a----%0a%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210421-175202-50550#%0a* [-21.04.2021 - 10:52-] || TA_audrey marked as complete%0a#foxend 210421-175202-50550#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0aSummary: \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aRepetition clefts in North American and U.K. english%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aIn North American and U.K. English, speakers frequently use repetition clefts to emphasize information they are trying to convey. They occur more frequently in spoken situations rather than written ones because they are ungrammatical. However, they are still acceptable in spoken situations because they are similar to wh-clefts:%0a    - Ex: “WHAT HE WANTS is A GOOD JOB”%0a    - Ex: “A GOOD JOB is WHAT HE WANTS”%0aRepetition clefts repeat the subject and verb of the clause the speaker wants to emphasize. They take 2 possible forms:%0a    1. Wh-phrase+ be/is + complete sentence %0a        - Ex: What he wants is HE WANTS A GOOD JOB%0a    2. Complete sentence + be/is + wh-phrase%0a        - Ex: HE WANTS A GOOD JOB is what he wants%0aA Wh-phrase begins with a question word (who, what, where, when, how). However, not all Wh-words are acceptable in repetition clefts. “what” is the most universally accepted Wh-word that can be used in repetition clefts. “who” and “which” are frequently considered unnatural or unacceptable to use in repetition clefts. Multiple wh-words can also be used:%0a    - Ex: WHO ordered WHAT is John ordered steak and Mary (ordered) salad.%0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:GradedBy: TA_audrey:)
